<p>
    Based on over 2,000 pages of law enforcement communication records, obtained by record request forms, High Country news released this article, talking about how the Federal Government, stalked and harassed protesters, simply for living near / being in an indigenous community that opposed the mines creation. Ka'ila Farrell-Smith, a member from the Klamath Tribe in Oregon, grew up deeply involved in the community fight for Indigenous rights. She stated specifically, that members since the 1970's have been repeatedly stalked and harassed by multiple different federal agencies. All later confirmed by declassified government records.
</p>


<p id="topicOneMore" style="display: none;">
    Law enforcement personnel, specifically FBI, Homeland Security, and multiple others privately worked alongside mine security to repeatedly stalk protesters. Tracking everything, from their social media to the video surveillance cameras on their campsite. All said, 10 agencies were monitoring the protesters, that being the FBI, The Bureau of Land Management, Humboldt County Sheriff's Department (in Nevada, not California), Bureau of Indian Affairs, Nevada State Police Highway Patrol, Winnemucca Police Department, and the Nevada Threat Analysis Center. The reason that was given in order to justify this repeated stalking and harassment, was due to the protesters being put under the, "potential terrorists" tag. That giving the federal government full unrestricted access to all information that pertains to you. As a result of the constant stalking, only one protester was arrested. Having a nonexistent threat essentially. 

    In specific, the FBI was tracking Gary McKinney. A member of the Duck Valley Shoshone-Paiute Tribe. He leads annual prayer rides, a practice where Indigenous Community members travel on horseback for hundreds of miles. Which is also protected under the Religious Freedom Act. The FBI tracked his activity, informing other agencies as well of this. The former FBI contractor was not yet licensed to even be doing private investigations under Nevada law, yet still was allowed to continuously harass patrons. Pulling back, we enter the global scale, and that is telling. It shows that 85% of Lithium deposits are on, or near Indigenous Land, meaning that this level of exploitation is not going to end, but is just starting to pick up again. With a projected demand of over 350% by 2040, with the increasing needs by electric vehicles, as well as technology that relys more on this Precocious metal. This peaceful protest was labeled a possible terrorist convergence. A label used to then justify repeated harassment, in a targeted campaign by multiple federal agencies. This shows how governments use scare tactics in order to silence and suppress those that they try to trample over. 
</p>
